## 1. Identify Reachable vs Unreachable Objects

Write a small program where:

- You create an object user
- Create a second object profile that references user
- Then set user = null

Is the original user object still reachable? Why or why not?

let user = {
    id:1234,
    name:"John"
};
let profile = user;
console.log(profile);
console.log(user===profile);
let user = null;
console.log(user);

Yes, the original user object is still reachable.
In JavaScript, objects are stored and accessed by reference. When you write let profile = user;, you aren't copying the data; you are creating a second pointer to the same memory address.
Even after you set user = null, the profile variable still holds that reference. The object remains in memory because JavaScript's Garbage Collector only removes an object when there are zero references pointing to it.
Since profile still points to the object, you can still access { id: 1234, name: "John" } through it.
## 2. Simulate and Break a Cyclic Reference

Observe how cyclic references can cause memory retention.

- Create two objects a and b
- Make them reference each other (a.ref = b and b.ref = a)
- Nullify external references to both

Explain why this may or may not cause a memory leak. Add a.ref = null; b.ref = null; and explain how it helps

let a = { id: 1 };
let b = { id: 2 };

// 1. Create cyclic reference
a.ref = b;
b.ref = a;

// 2. Break the cycle (Optional but helpful for old GCs)
a.ref = null;
b.ref = null;

// 3. Nullify external references (Crucial for memory recovery)
a = null;
b = null;


console.log(b);
console.log(a);

## 3. DOM Leak Detection and Fix

Learn how DOM elements and closures can create memory leaks.

- Create a button using JavaScript
- Add an event listener that references a variable outside the listener
- Remove the button from the DOM, but not the event listener

Identify the leak & fix it.

function createLeakingButton() {
  const largeData = new Array(1000000).fill('💣'); // Simulates a large memory footprint
  const btn = document.createElement('button');
  btn.innerText = 'Click Me';

  // The Closure: The listener keeps a reference to 'largeData' from the outer scope
  btn.addEventListener('click', function() {
    console.log('Data length:', largeData.length);
  });

  document.body.appendChild(btn);

  // Simulating removing the button from the DOM
  setTimeout(() => {
    document.body.removeChild(btn);
    console.log('Button removed from DOM, but the listener and largeData persist in memory!');
  }, 2000);
}

createLeakingButton();

Why does this leak?
Persistent References: The Garbage Collector only deletes objects it can no longer "reach."
Closure Retention: Because the event listener function is still attached to the btn object, it holds onto the largeData variable via the closure.
Dangling Object: Since the listener wasn't explicitly removed using removeEventListener, the btn object (and everything it references) stays in memory as long as the listener exists.
